<br>
Whereas most Japanese children learn Kanji through repeatedly writing/re-writing the characters, this is probably not the fastest, best way for an adult foreigner to learn Kanji.  Remember, a Japanese kid needs to know how to WRITE BY HAND, which is significantly more difficult than what a foreigner needs to do (recognize a word well enough to read it, or find it on a word-processor's menu while typing).<br>
<br>
I find that the best way is to find out what each kanji's PICTURES mean, and that helps me to understand the meaning of the kanji.  Being able to WRITE a kanji is of decidedly lesser importance, and can be classified as a &quot;luxury item&quot; on my list of priorities.<br>
<br>
BOOKS and SOFTWARE:<br>
-----------<br>
<br>
Electronically, see if you can get a copy of Kan-taro as a learning program.  It shows mini-animations, as pictures morph into kanji and then back into pictures.<br>
<br>
In paper-books, I strongly recommend a few softcover books (from amazon or powells books or wherever):<br>
&quot;KANJI Pict.o.graphix&quot; by Michael Rowley<br>
ISBN 0-9628137-0-2 (very very good, slightly wide book)<br>
<br>
&quot;Read Japanese Today&quot; by Len Walsh (Tuttle Publishers)<br>
ISBN 0-8048-0496-6 (currently in its 49th printing...WOW.  Small, truly pocket-size...good for reading while you commute or wait in the dentist's office)<br>
<br>
and finally, ALSO truly pocket-sized, <br>
&quot;Kanji Starter&quot; by Daiki Kusuya, published bi IGC Muse.<br>
ISBN 4-925080-48-2<br>
This one is merely so-so, but not bad.<br>
<br>
