<br>
anyway, i had a *very* traditional teacher, and hella` killer kanji tests every week back when I was in Uni, so for me, learning to write kanji by hand was unfortunately a requirement.  Not that it matters, since I have steadily forgotten most of them since graduating.. *sniff*.  I was always envious of people who could learn kanji by any means other than rote repetition...!!  ARrrrrgghh!!! panda jealous!  <br>
<br>
if you`re just trying to read japanese, and writing is of less importance (which now-a-days with the advent of computers, cellphones and other electronic means of writing japanese is becoming more and more true....) then you can save yourself boatloads of time by following seth`s advise and skipping the whole write-the-same-character-100-times bit.  Which come to think of it, means you can go out to the bars and whatnot while poor little pandas are locked in their rooms on saturday nights with only a solitary flickering lightbulb illuminating sheaves of paper scrawled with illegible characters.   ....  <br>
<br>
